The behaviour of solutions at these points is given by
\ba
f(x)\sim x^{c_i}\, ,\hspace{1cm}c_1=-1\;\; c_2=0\;\; c_3=1\, ,\hspace{1cm}
x&\longrightarrow& 0\; ;
\nonumber \\ \nonumber
f(x)\sim (x+1)^{b_i}\, ,\hspace{1cm}b_1=0\;\; b_2=1+\lambda\;\;
b_3=2\, ,\hspace{1cm}x&\longrightarrow& -1\; ;
\\ \nonumber
f(x)\sim x^{a_i}\, ,\hspace{1cm}x&\longrightarrow& \infty \; ,
\ea
where $a_1\ge a_2\ge a_3$ are the roots of the characteristic equation
\be
\mlab{char}
a^3+\lambda x^2+(\lambda -1)x+\lambda =0\, .
\ee
 In fact,
\[
f(z)\equiv
{_3F_2}\left(
\begin{array}{l}
a_1,a_2,a_3;\hspace{5mm}\\
\hspace{2cm}z\\b_1,b_2
\end{array}
\right)
\]
satisfies
\ba
&&z^2(1-z)f''' +\left[ 1+b_1+b_2-(3+a_1+a_2+a_3)z\right] f''\\
&+&\left[ b_1b_2-(1+a_1+a_2+a_3+a_1a_2+a_2a_3+a_3a_1)z\right]
f'-a_1a_2a_3f=0 \, . \nonumber \mlab{hyper2}
\ea
On comparing \mref{hyper1} and \mref{hyper2} we make the identifications
\[
b_1+b_2=-1-\lambda\, , \;\;\; b_1b_2=\lambda
\]
so we can take $b_1=-1$ and $b_2=-\lambda$. Also
\[
a_1+a_2+a_3=-\lambda\, , \;\;\;
a_1a_2+a_2a_3+a_3a_1=-(1-\lambda )\, , \;\;\;
a_1+a_2+a_3=-\lambda\, ,
\]
so that the $a_i$ are the roots of the characteristic equation
\mref{char},
which we have ordered for definiteness as follows:
$a_1\ge a_2\ge a_3$.

We choose, as a fundamental set of linearly independent solutions,
$f_i(z)$, of \mref{hyper1},





which are particularly useful near $z=x+1 \longrightarrow \infty$.


\be
f_i(z)=\left\{ \prod_{\nu =1}^3 \frac{\Gamma (\alpha_i+\gamma_\nu )}
{\Gamma (\alpha_i+\alpha_\nu +1)}\right\} z^{-\alpha_i}
{_3F_2}\left(
\begin{array}{l}
\alpha_i+\gamma_1 , \alpha_i+\gamma_2 , -\alpha_i+\gamma_3 \hspace{5mm}\\
\hspace{6cm}\frac{1}{z}\\
\alpha_i-\alpha_1+1 , \alpha_i-\alpha_2 , \alpha_i-\alpha_3+1 \hspace{5mm}
\end{array}
\right)  \mlab{fi}
\ee


The generalized equation,  of $n$'th order, with three
regular singularities at $z=0,1,\infty$, has the form
\[
z^n(1-z)\frac{d^nf}{dz^n}
+\sum_{\nu =0}^{n-1}(a_\nu -b_\nu z^\nu ) \frac{d^\nu f}{dz^\nu}=0\, .
\]



\left.{
\frac{(4\lambda^3-18\lambda^2+18\lambda+54)^{\frac{1}{3}}}




It would be interesting also to
obtain a value  $\gamma_m<1$, and such models are worthy of further
investigation.



